  "slug": "pumpkin-pie-thanksgiving",
  "title": "Thanksgiving pumpkin pie",
  "subtitle": "Spiced pumpkin custard in a shortcrust shell",
  "excerpt": "The American Thanksgiving classic: a shortcrust pastry base blind-baked, filled with a spiced pumpkin custard, and baked low until the centre is just set with a slight wobble. One 23 cm pie, serving eight.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Amelia Simmons, American Cookery (1796), Project Gutenberg: the earliest documented American pumpkin pie recipe. Fannie Farmer, The Boston Cooking-School Cook Book (1896), Project Gutenberg: gives the canonical spice profile (cinnamon, ginger, cloves) and the custard ratio used here. USDA Bureau of Home Economics (1920s, public domain): pumpkin-pie filling guidance establishes the bake-at-low-temperature rule that keeps the custard smooth.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pumpkin pie is a spiced custard baked in a shortcrust shell. The pumpkin is cooked and puréed (or taken straight from a tin); the custard is eggs, brown sugar, double cream and a heavy hand of cinnamon, ginger and cloves; the base is a sweet shortcrust blind-baked until pale gold so the wet filling does not seep through.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Worked at a low temperature once the filling goes in, the custard sets smoothly without cracking. The cue at the end is the wobble, the edges look set, the centre still moves slightly under a shake of the tin. Pull the pie at that point and the residual heat carries it the rest of the way.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
